      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was trying to make hollandaise for brunch but it just turned into a greasy mess. it like completely separated and looks oily instead of creamy. why does that happen? how do i fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hollandaise is a delicate *emulsion* of egg yolks and butter, and if you've ever tried to make it, you know that the butter must be emulsified into the yolks, not just melted on top. If the butter separates, it's usually because the fat was added too quickly or the heat was too high, causing the emulsion to break.\n\nThe first thing you need to do is stop the heat immediately and whisk the yolks vigorously until they are thick and pale. Then, slowly drizzle in the warm (not hot) butter while whisking constantly. If the mixture looks too thick, you can add a splash of warm water or lemon juice to loosen it up, but be careful not to overheat it again.\n\nIf you have a little bit of patience, you can also try a \"basting\" technique where you whisk the yolks in a small bowl over a double boiler, then slowly pour the warm butter into it while whisking. This helps create a stable emulsion that will hold its creamy shape.\n\nAnd don't worry, if you accidentally overheat the mixture, you can always add a splash of cold water to re-emulsify it, though it might need a",
