      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tip. i tried a bit of the water thing like u said but it's still acting weird and looking all clumpy and oily. i feel like i'm doing everything right but it just keeps falling apart every time i try to fix it. is there anything else that could be causing this? it's super frustrating.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"clumpy and oily\" disaster! That is the classic sign of a broken emulsion, but don't worry, you're not alone in this frustrating struggle. It often happens when the butter is too hot or the yolks are too cold, causing the fat to seize up rather than blend.\n\nHere is a secret trick to save your brunch: **The \"Ice Bath\" method.**\n\nFirst, cool the yolks down to room temperature (or even chill them in the fridge for 10 minutes). Then, take a small bowl and place it over a pot of simmering water (double boiler) to warm the yolks gently. While the yolks are warming, take a separate small bowl of ice water.\n\nNow, slowly whisk the warm yolks into the ice water. This will shock the fat molecules and help them re-emulsify. Once the mixture looks smooth and pale, you can slowly drizzle in the warm butter while whisking vigorously.\n\nIf you still get clumps, try adding a tiny pinch of a stabilizer like cornstarch or a dash of lemon juice to the yolks before adding the butter. It acts like a glue to hold the fat together.\n\nRemember,",
      "source": "target",
